The setup() function runs only once when the Arduino is powered on or reset. It is used to initialize pins, sensors, Serial communication, and other settings.

The loop() function runs continuously after setup() finishes. It contains the main program logic and keeps executing repeatedly.

If a long delay() is used inside loop(), the Arduino cannot perform other tasks during that time. As a result, sensor readings become slow, button presses may be missed, and the system becomes less responsive.

The non-blocking alternative is to use the millis() function, which allows the Arduino to perform multiple tasks simultaneously without stopping the execution of the program.
